statement.p:
 Consider a vertex v with ring distance d=d(v,t) satisfying 2^j \leq d < 2^{j+1}.





 Let

A = \{ w \mid d(w,t) \leq d/2 \}

be the set of vertices that are "at most half the distance from t as v." Explain why

|A|=d+1

and why

\frac{d}{2} \leq d(v,w) \leq \frac{3d}{2}

for all w \in A.




There are d+1 vertices in A= \{ t - d/2, \ldots , t + d/2 \}. Meanwhile, vertex v satisties d(v,t)=d, so the closest w \in A can be is d(v,w)=d/2 and the farthest that it can be is d(v,w) = 3d/2.










 Prove that

\displaystyle{\Pr[v \mbox{'s long-range contact is in } A] \geq  \frac{1}{3 \log n}}.








\Pr[v \mbox{'s long-range contact is in } A]
&\geq (d+1) \cdot  C \cdot \frac{1}{3d/2}


& \geq (d+1) \frac{1}{ 2 \log n}  \cdot \frac{2}{3d}


& > \frac{1}{ 3\log n}













 Use part (b) to prove that

\displaystyle{\Pr[\mbox{round } j \mbox{ lasts at least } i  \mbox{ steps}] \leq  \left( 1 - \frac{1}{ 3 \log n} \right)^{i-1}}.






If v's long range contact is in A, then we end the round after that step. So the probability that we take at least i steps is

\left( 1 - \frac{1}{3 \log n} \right)^{i-1}
